"no-referrer">U.S. Navy</a></p></figcaption></figure><p>The Army has its own bespoke font, with the name “G.I.” (which seems like a missed opportunity with all the cool terminology available). The document says the name “...is inspired by the U.S. Army’s people and unique culture. The character and spirit of the font align with the no-nonsense brand identity principles of being clear, confident, and human.” </p><figure><img src="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/GNr_Zps4IoGoxoxwkkz5lJjJQdnB0wUT-tnhRiWtk5U=/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmVhdXRpZnVscHVibGljZGF0YS5jb20vY29udGVudC9pbWFnZXMvMjAyMy8xMC9TY3JlZW5zaG90LTIwMjMtMTAtMDMtYXQtMS4zMy4wOS1BTS0xLnBuZw==" alt="The Army and Navy Style Guides" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/pgdzb6Inxky5sn-d-cGAEu6VWgsCtBm92mCq-9LhSjg=/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmVhdXRpZnVscHVibGljZGF0YS5jb20vY29udGVudC9pbWFnZXMvc2l6ZS93NjAwLzIwMjMvMTAvU2NyZWVuc2hvdC0yMDIzLTEwLTAzLWF0LTEuMzMuMDktQU0tMS5wbmc= 600w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/jNXWC3P3m4YZZe6gXI7BXzi_bM1t7YL4Qyk3w71ahYk=/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmVhdXRpZnVscHVibGljZGF0YS5jb20vY29udGVudC9pbWFnZXMvc2l6ZS93MTAwMC8yMDIzLzEwL1NjcmVlbnNob3QtMjAyMy0xMC0wMy1hdC0xLjMzLjA5LUFNLTEucG5n 1000w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/gyO1uLM5tEfpsXJBlW6mNlmQSaSQNO1RaAMweF2JIHE=/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmVhdXRpZnVscHVibGljZGF0YS5jb20vY29udGVudC9pbWFnZXMvc2l6ZS93MTYwMC8yMDIzLzEwL1NjcmVlbnNob3QtMjAyMy0xMC0wMy1hdC0xLjMzLjA5LUFNLTEucG5n 1600w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/1BYIz4EpmbbJgaT_7aSHuxeGkYYCggEd845lTIn_ws4=/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmVhdXRpZnVscHVibGljZGF0YS5jb20vY29udGVudC9pbWFnZXMvc2l6ZS93MjQwMC8yMDIzLzEwL1NjcmVlbnNob3QtMjAyMy0xMC0wMy1hdC0xLjMzLjA5LUFNLTEucG5n 2400w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px" loading="lazy"/><img src="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/0oUSAajuc9sO6eeoCvwt5VvqLBZDSV4dDHf58KBcI3c=/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmVhdXRpZnVscHVibGljZGF0YS5jb20vY29udGVudC9pbWFnZXMvMjAyMy8xMC9TY3JlZW5zaG90LTIwMjMtMTAtMDMtYXQtMS4xNS4yNS1BTS0xLnBuZw==" alt="The Army and Navy Style Guides" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/s-adUcwL2wHZUvQPiBZZGqXIRHQvRUIFmezYPd0Eqw8=/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmVhdXRpZnVscHVibGljZGF0YS5jb20vY29udGVudC9pbWFnZXMvc2l6ZS93NjAwLzIwMjMvMTAvU2NyZWVuc2hvdC0yMDIzLTEwLTAzLWF0LTEuMTUuMjUtQU0tMS5wbmc= 600w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/0oUSAajuc9sO6eeoCvwt5VvqLBZDSV4dDHf58KBcI3c=/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmVhdXRpZnVscHVibGljZGF0YS5jb20vY29udGVudC9pbWFnZXMvMjAyMy8xMC9TY3JlZW5zaG90LTIwMjMtMTAtMDMtYXQtMS4xNS4yNS1BTS0xLnBuZw== 872w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px" loading="lazy"/><figcaption><p>Left: A page from the Army Brand Guidelines. Right: A page from the Navy Brand Guidelines. Source: U.S. Army, <a href="https://etoolbox.cnrc.navy.mil/assets/documents/BrandGuidelines_Digital.pdf?ref=beautifulpublicdata.com" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">U.S. Navy</a></p></figcaption></figure><p>There are reminders that this typeface is for military business first, and less about aesthetics. The zero features a slash which was “...designed to embody the utilitarian spirit of the U.S. Army” and prevent confusion with a capital O, says the document. The numeral 1 and capital I are also clearly distinct. The font can be used for 120 languages and their unique typographic marks. </p><p>One of the most fascinating sections of this document describes all aspects of how photography is used in Army communications. The rules are organized by the fundamental photographic principles of color, composition and perspective. </p><p>“Warm tones and natural light create an authentic, human feel, and the golden quality of light recalls the U.S. Army’s brand colors while expressing a mood of possibility” reads the document. It calls for the use of bold images with strong contrast, toned to reflect the colors from the Army palette. Also, the use of black and white photos are discouraged. </p><p>Compositions are to be clear and direct, and free of any dramatic effects, and notes  that photographs “...should feel like an authentic moment, unstaged.” When describing perspective, the photography should provide “...an immersive, dynamic, and authentic window on life inside the U.S. Army, as experienced from a very human, first-person perspective.”</p><figure><img src="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/rIHfQUiOy-kVxpJXfB48w2VwQ1cHH7fK2FXsZuV9p8g=/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmVhdXRpZnVscHVibGljZGF0YS5jb20vY29udGVudC9pbWFnZXMvMjAyMy8xMC9TY3JlZW5zaG90LTIwMjMtMTAtMDMtYXQtMS4zMC40Ny1BTS0xLnBuZw==" alt="The Army and Navy Style Guides" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/fe1jBY5zKwZu7BblNbAqcLx-qYje8xcK8ufCjRo8mmc=/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmVhdXRpZnVscHVibGljZGF0YS5jb20vY29udGVudC9pbWFnZXMvc2l6ZS93NjAwLzIwMjMvMTAvU2NyZWVuc2hvdC0yMDIzLTEwLTAzLWF0LTEuMzAuNDctQU0tMS5wbmc= 600w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/1NepUfAhp4K_cakmlQnS3jgAKT8AaJzmg918gHDBzEI=/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmVhdXRpZnVscHVibGljZGF0YS5jb20vY29udGVudC9pbWFnZXMvc2l6ZS93MTAwMC8yMDIzLzEwL1NjcmVlbnNob3QtMjAyMy0xMC0wMy1hdC0xLjMwLjQ3LUFNLTEucG5n 1000w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/GlgDCypfI2Jf9KSEYYv7WcBQjs6whoHLQGrepAgRfwM=/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmVhdXRpZnVscHVibGljZGF0YS5jb20vY29udGVudC9pbWFnZXMvc2l6ZS93MTYwMC8yMDIzLzEwL1NjcmVlbnNob3QtMjAyMy0xMC0wMy1hdC0xLjMwLjQ3LUFNLTEucG5n 1600w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/LAfR46wx1SEt__m4jSM6DGa2xLgaBwbmjfm96qjh1PE=/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmVhdXRpZnVscHVibGljZGF0YS5jb20vY29udGVudC9pbWFnZXMvc2l6ZS93MjQwMC8yMDIzLzEwL1NjcmVlbnNob3QtMjAyMy0xMC0wMy1hdC0xLjMwLjQ3LUFNLTEucG5n 2400w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px" loading="lazy"/><img src="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/SHu_0cCpqa_OmoizZcENn4XSOHmjjsac7vz23RUoaLk=/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmVhdXRpZnVscHVibGljZGF0YS5jb20vY29udGVudC9pbWFnZXMvMjAyMy8xMC9TY3JlZW5zaG90LTIwMjMtMTAtMDMtYXQtMS4xOC4yMS1BTS0yLnBuZw==" alt="The Army and Navy Style Guides" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/avmUgxtTGVut0DsbPkUbD_jDr8QfM-nhxPuisy7nopI=/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmVhdXRpZnVscHVibGljZGF0YS5jb20vY29udGVudC9pbWFnZXMvc2l6ZS93NjAwLzIwMjMvMTAvU2NyZWVuc2hvdC0yMDIzLTEwLTAzLWF0LTEuMTguMjEtQU0tMi5wbmc= 600w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/SHu_0cCpqa_OmoizZcENn4XSOHmjjsac7vz23RUoaLk=/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmVhdXRpZnVscHVibGljZGF0YS5jb20vY29udGVudC9pbWFnZXMvMjAyMy8xMC9TY3JlZW5zaG90LTIwMjMtMTAtMDMtYXQtMS4xOC4yMS1BTS0yLnBuZw== 915w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px" loading="lazy"/><figcaption><p>Left: A page from the Army Brand Guidelines. Right: A page from the Navy Brand Guidelines. Source: U.S. Army, <a href="https://etoolbox.cnrc.navy.mil/assets/documents/BrandGuidelines_Digital.pdf?ref=beautifulpublicdata.com" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">U.S. Navy</a></p></figcaption></figure><p>The focus on showing the positive human side of Army personnel runs through this whole document. It encourages depicting soldiers both in and out of uniform  following their passions, developing their careers in the Army and forging strong social connections with teammates. </p><p>Diversity is also a theme emphasized noting “The U.S. Army and its members reflect the diverse geography and population of the United States, and U.S. Army photography must do the same.” There are some interesting caveats with regards to photographs depicting soldiers in uniform. The correct placement of patches and uniform accessories are emphasized, as is the importance of “proper styling and grooming of apparel, accessories, and equipment. ”</p><a href="https://www.beautifulpublicdata.com/subscribe#/portal/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">Subscribe to Beautiful Public Data!</a><p>But the most stark warning relates to the depiction of weapons appearing in Army photos. The document warns in unusual seriousness “...under no circumstances may a weapon of any kind ever appear, in moving or still imagery, to be pointed in the direction of the lens; e.g., at the viewer.” </p><h3 id="the-army%E2%80%99s-voice-%E2%80%9Cnot-cold-or-terse%E2%80%9D">The Army’s Voice: “Not cold or terse”</h3><p>For an organization as large as the Army, the challenge of speaking with one cohesive voice is significant, and the guide has some suggestions here too. The Army wants its voice to be factual and concise, but not devoid of humanity. “We are not cold or terse, despite our direct tone.” </p><p>While the voice should be confident and “secure in our identity” it also aims for humility. “We don’t put others down, think we are above growth, or believe we are too strong for support.” But at the end of the day, this voice is stern and focused on the task at hand: “We don’t make decisions based on emotion. We don’t use slang or trendy language.”</p><h3 id="navy-forged-by-the-sea">Navy: Forged By the Sea</h3><p>After reading through the Army’s comprehensive brand guidelines, it is especially informative to see how it compares and contrasts to its sea-based brethren, the U.S. Navy. The Navy’s brand guidelines doc shown here is from 2019, and while it is only half the length of the Army’s guidelines document it is equally slick and well designed and is organized in a similar way. </p><figure><img src="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/AlsPnDo4N-BMGkNQSlGr6koKrlwnId7WR0vTg3Uan_0=/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmVhdXRpZnVscHVibGljZGF0YS5jb20vY29udGVudC9pbWFnZXMvMjAyMy8xMC9uYXZ5LTExLnBuZw==" alt="The Army and Navy Style Guides" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/VCvWc-0OHl-i3lub-rQidFYEl6DSpzo-YUWwfSrRIwQ=/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmVhdXRpZnVscHVibGljZGF0YS5jb20vY29udGVudC9pbWFnZXMvc2l6ZS93NjAwLzIwMjMvMTAvbmF2eS0xMS5wbmc= 600w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/AlsPnDo4N-BMGkNQSlGr6koKrlwnId7WR0vTg3Uan_0=/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmVhdXRpZnVscHVibGljZGF0YS5jb20vY29udGVudC9pbWFnZXMvMjAyMy8xMC9uYXZ5LTExLnBuZw== 776w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px" loading="lazy"/><figcaption>A page from the Navy Brand Guidelines. Source: <a href="https://etoolbox.cnrc.navy.mil/assets/documents/BrandGuidelines_Digital.pdf?ref=beautifulpublicdata.com" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">U.S. Navy</a></figcaption></figure><p>Right off the bat, the actual name of the fighting force is re-branded as “America’s Navy”, with no other variations allowed. “It’s important for America to feel ownership of their Navy—the largest, strongest and most technologically advanced in the world,” reads the document. </p><figure><img src="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/mIFOrVfmvIPUscP0ab0MBftVUz12uQjfkDpa-kcWERY=/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmVhdXRpZnVscHVibGljZGF0YS5jb20vY29udGVudC9pbWFnZXMvMjAyMy8xMC9TY3JlZW5zaG90LTIwMjMtMTAtMDMtYXQtMS4zNS4yOS1BTS0xLnBuZw==" alt="The Army and Navy Style Guides" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/vqVhmwM1R_uL1wWPcvaUE7LRgqSXXIElCIGGwHgAM54=/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmVhdXRpZnVscHVibGljZGF0YS5jb20vY29udGVudC9pbWFnZXMvc2l6ZS93NjAwLzIwMjMvMTAvU2NyZWVuc2hvdC0yMDIzLTEwLTAzLWF0LTEuMzUuMjktQU0tMS5wbmc= 600w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/_6v6RVNJA6hRBmLO1-__fkMPmWRzSITA7K4AF0xrgWE=/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmVhdXRpZnVscHVibGljZGF0YS5jb20vY29udGVudC9pbWFnZXMvc2l6ZS93MTAwMC8yMDIzLzEwL1NjcmVlbnNob3QtMjAyMy0xMC0wMy1hdC0xLjM1LjI5LUFNLTEucG5n 1000w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/v9qSu2mOk4xLaPrTErB-YVEZXC0S6cI3yDNvzUmlBHY=/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmVhdXRpZnVscHVibGljZGF0YS5jb20vY29udGVudC9pbWFnZXMvc2l6ZS93MTYwMC8yMDIzLzEwL1NjcmVlbnNob3QtMjAyMy0xMC0wMy1hdC0xLjM1LjI5LUFNLTEucG5n 1600w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/_kdGbSbl3NkWdQUc2MV5F0hPo4PB1LpkFBYzhmwUeVw=/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmVhdXRpZnVscHVibGljZGF0YS5jb20vY29udGVudC9pbWFnZXMvc2l6ZS93MjQwMC8yMDIzLzEwL1NjcmVlbnNob3QtMjAyMy0xMC0wMy1hdC0xLjM1LjI5LUFNLTEucG5n 2400w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px" loading="lazy"/><img src="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/RIHDqR8ViZvSQxB4m3y-jjjp6uiQ4Ps4SCCt1jOnhyQ=/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmVhdXRpZnVscHVibGljZGF0YS5jb20vY29udGVudC9pbWFnZXMvMjAyMy8xMC9TY3JlZW5zaG90LTIwMjMtMTAtMDMtYXQtMS4xOC4xNC1BTS0xLnBuZw==" alt="The Army and Navy Style Guides" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/64MksUu0xqTRnslE1ysEkOvAig2rV7TtdAakfTAcL04=/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmVhdXRpZnVscHVibGljZGF0YS5jb20vY29udGVudC9pbWFnZXMvc2l6ZS93NjAwLzIwMjMvMTAvU2NyZWVuc2hvdC0yMDIzLTEwLTAzLWF0LTEuMTguMTQtQU0tMS5wbmc= 600w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/RIHDqR8ViZvSQxB4m3y-jjjp6uiQ4Ps4SCCt1jOnhyQ=/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmVhdXRpZnVscHVibGljZGF0YS5jb20vY29udGVudC9pbWFnZXMvMjAyMy8xMC9TY3JlZW5zaG90LTIwMjMtMTAtMDMtYXQtMS4xOC4xNC1BTS0xLnBuZw== 914w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px" loading="lazy"/><figcaption><p>Left: A page from the Army Brand Guidelines. Right: A page from the Navy Brand Guidelines. Source: U.S. Army, <a href="https://etoolbox.cnrc.navy.mil/assets/documents/BrandGuidelines_Digital.pdf?ref=beautifulpublicdata.com" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">U.S. Navy</a></p></figcaption></figure><p>There is definitely a different, more dramatic personality peeking through these guidelines, and the Navy brand statement stirs up some positively cinematic imagery in this prose: </p><blockquote><em>“The sea is the greatest force on earth.<br/>It reaches impossible speeds, depths and distances. It cannot be beaten with the strongest fist, cut with the sharpest knife or stopped by the fastest bullet.”<br/>…<br/>“Water and salt flow through our veins in the same proportion as the sea. That mighty force is the lifeblood of the greatest Navy ever to sail unstoppably upon it, slip stealthily beneath it or fly unchallenged above it”   </em></blockquote><h3 id="we%E2%80%99re-doing-six-pillars">We’re doing six pillars</h3><p>While the Army’s brand rests upon two (four) pillars, the Navy throws down with SIX:</p><ul><li>Strength</li><li>Opportunity</li><li>Direction</li><li>Teamwork</li><li>Creative innovation</li><li>Meaningful Adventure</li></ul><p>The logo for the Navy features the “America’s Navy” wordmark sitting beside an eagle with a shield for a chest, perched on an anchor.</p><p>Drawing on the steely, cool hues of the salty ocean the Navy’s four color palette consists of Navy blue, followed by blue, light gray and yellow. </p><figure><img src="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/cRS_A21CUtqvcyI0ieJSikMdHkG92M5f2AumhkMPPmA=/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmVhdXRpZnVscHVibGljZGF0YS5jb20vY29udGVudC9pbWFnZXMvMjAyMy8xMC9TY3JlZW5zaG90LTIwMjMtMTAtMDMtYXQtMS4xNy4wOC1BTS0xLTEucG5n" alt="The Army and Navy Style Guides" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/uOjNouuef-nOGv_66tRID-pS75aT7hdcr82Z2qzeKZA=/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmVhdXRpZnVscHVibGljZGF0YS5jb20vY29udGVudC9pbWFnZXMvc2l6ZS93NjAwLzIwMjMvMTAvU2NyZWVuc2hvdC0yMDIzLTEwLTAzLWF0LTEuMTcuMDgtQU0tMS0xLnBuZw== 600w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/cRS_A21CUtqvcyI0ieJSikMdHkG92M5f2AumhkMPPmA=/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmVhdXRpZnVscHVibGljZGF0YS5jb20vY29udGVudC9pbWFnZXMvMjAyMy8xMC9TY3JlZW5zaG90LTIwMjMtMTAtMDMtYXQtMS4xNy4wOC1BTS0xLTEucG5n 872w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px" loading="lazy"/></figure><p>Photography is encouraged to be slightly desaturated, high contrast and toned with “a subtle steel gray” color to evoke a cinematic feeling which should focus on people as the main focus as much as possible. </p><p>The Navy sure knows how to name things, calling its own font “Liberator”. The document shows the appropriate use of the thick block letters spelling out phrases like “PEACE DOESN’T PRESERVE ITSELF”.</p>🙏🏻<strong>Did you enjoy this post?</strong><br/>You can subscribe to our newsletter to get future posts delivered to your inbox for free. 👉🏻 📫 <a href="https://www.beautifulpublicdata.com/subscribe#/portal/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">Subscribe now</a>.<br/><br/><strong>Sharing is caring</strong><br/>📣 If you think your followers or friends may like it, please consider sharing it.<br/><br/>🙋🏻‍♀️ If you have any suggestions, comments or requests, please email them to <a href="mailto:beautifulpublicdata@gmail.com" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">beautifulpublicdata@gmail.com</a><br/><br/>Thanks for reading!<br/>- Jon Keegan <br/>Threads: <a href="https://www.threads.net/@jonkeeganstories?ref=beautifulpublicdata.com" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">@jonkeeganstories</a><br/>Mastodon: <a href="https://ma